34. In grep \| is used for OR operation.               
eg. cat /etc/ passwd | grep -v "false\|nologin"         
eg. cat /etc/ passwd | grep -v "false\|nologin" | cut -d":" -f1     
here cut is use for delimiter d as -d ":" and -f1 shows first field               
eg. cat /etc/ passwd | grep -v "false\|nologin" | tr ":" " "        
here tr works same as cut but here we can replace ":" with " "        
eg. cat /etc/ passwd | grep -v "false\|nologin" | tr ":" " " | column -t          
here column -t is use to make a table like form of our result 
eg. cat /etc/ passwd | grep -v "false\|nologin" | tr ":" " " | awk '{print $1, $NF}'            
here lets take an example like:       
root    x     0     0     root    /root     /bin/bash                      
 │        │     │    │      │       │              │                            
 $1     $2   $3  $4    $5     $6            $7        
so here  print use to display and $1 is first field and $NF used to display last field.  We can also use -F: for delimit directly wihout using any other tool for delimiter.      
grep "cry0l1t3" /etc/ passwd | awk -F: '{print $1 "," $3}'                        
eg. cat /etc/ passwd | grep -v "false\|nologin" | tr ":" " " | awk '{print $1, $NF}' | sed 's/bin/HTB/g'        
here sed is an stream editor which is used to replace any text where                
here s is Substitute             
here bin is the word to search             
here HTB is the word which replace bin              
here g is used for all occurence to be replaced by HTB        
eg. cat /etc/ passwd | grep -v "false\|nologin" | tr ":" " " | awk '{print $1, $NF}' | wc -l         
here wc -l is used to count number of lines occured      
