37.     RegEx(Regular Expression)         
Operators	Description          
(a)	-The round brackets are used to group parts of a regex. Within the brackets, you can define further patterns which should be processed together.            
[a-z]	-The square brackets are used to define character classes. Inside the brackets, you can specify a list of characters to search for.            
{1,10}	-The curly brackets are used to define quantifiers. Inside the brackets, you can specify a number or a range that indicates how often a previous pattern should be repeated.               
|	-Also called the OR operator and shows results when one of the two expressions matches                
.*	-Operates similarly to an AND operator by displaying results only when both expressions are present and match in the specified order        
To use RegEx in grep we have to do        
grep -E         
eg.   grep -E "(my|false)" /etc/ passwd          
here we are saying to find line which contains have my or false            
eg.     grep -E "(my.*false)" /etc/ passwd            
here we are saying to find line which contains have my and false                
eg. grep -v -E "#" /etc/ ssh/ sshd_config | grep -v "^$" 
here we use ^$ to filter the blank line in-between         
where ^ means start of line and $ means end of line            
eg.  https://www.inlanefreight.com | grep -Eo "www.inlanefreight.com[^'\"]* | sort -u | wc 
eg.  grep -E "Permit[a-zA-Z0-9]*"  /etc/ ssh/ sshd_config             
here * is used to tell that occurance might be 0 to more        
here [ ] have alphabets and numbers to be serach and which should be occured after Permit word           
eg. grep -E '[A-Za-z]*Authentication' /etc/ ssh/ sshd_config 
eg. grep -E '^Password.*yes' /etc/ ssh/ sshd_config
eg. eg. grep -E 'yes$' /etc/ ssh/ sshd_config

